 fatigued, and working more while earning less. As one copilot reported, employees are so distracted "it’s almost a miracle that there wasn’t bent metal and dead people" at his airline. Although opinions like this are pervasive, for reasons discussed in this book, employees’ issues do not concern the right people—namely airline executives, aviation industry regulators, politicians, watchdog groups, or even the flying public—in the right way often enough. In contrast to popular notions that airliner accidents are a thing of the past, Fraher makes clear America is entering a period of unprecedented aviation risk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAeronauticszUnited StatesxSafety measuresxFinance. 0aAircraft accidentszUnited StatesxPreventionxFinance. 0aAirlinesxEmployeesxSalaries, etczUnited States. 0aAirlinesxEmployeesxSalaries, etc.zUnited States. 0aAirlineszUnited StatesxFinance. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History.  aaviation and finances, air travel safety, aviation industry, united airlines, government regulation, airline crashes, 2008 financial industry, aviation risk management, aviation industry regulation, aviation risk.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147049340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470493/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles